# Jam Session Fixes

## Root Causes Found & Fixed

### Bug 1: WebSocket Route Hidden by Static Mount
The `@app.websocket("/ws/{room_id}/{player_id}")` decorator was originally `@app.get(...)`, which is **not** a valid WebSocket endpoint. FastAPI silently rejected WebSocket upgrade requests with HTTP 404, meaning **no browser could ever connect** to the jam session.

### Bug 2: `KeyError` Crash in `ConnectionManager.add()`
When the first player connected: [add()](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/session_server.py#42-60) created the room set → called [broadcast_to_others()](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/session_server.py#77-96) → that method found an empty room → **deleted the room dict entry** → [add()](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/session_server.py#42-60) then tried `self.rooms[room_id].add(...)` → **`KeyError` crash** → connection silently dropped.

### Bug 3: Wrong WebSocket Port in Player Pages  
Both [piano-player.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/piano-player.html) and [drums-player.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/drums-player.html) had hardcoded `window.JAM_SESSION_WS_URL = 'ws://localhost:8765/ws'`, overriding the correct URL set by [jam-core.js](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/jam-core.js). This was **a different port entirely** from the running server (8502).

### Bug 4: Ngrok Routing Interference (Port Mapping)
When playing over ngrok, the AR camera and the Music fetch APIs (both running on separate backend HTTP ports like 8768 and 8766) were unreachable because ngrok only opens a tunnel to one port (8502). Fixed this by adding an **`httpx` reverse proxy route** to [session_server.py](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/session_server.py). Now, ngrok requests pointing to `.../api/` or `.../streamlit/` securely proxy internally to the correct Streamlit and Flask services.

### Bug 5: Piano Pitch Shifting Interference
In "Piano Player" mode, if a user's hand was too high or too low, the application would dynamically pitch-shift the note up or down (used for freeplay). This caused horrible interference when trying to play an actual song, because playing the correct note (e.g., C4) but holding the hand high would generate a C5. Fixed this by enforcing **strict exact note playback** when a song is actively playing, totally muting wrong fingers and overriding the pitch-shifter.

## Verified End-to-End

```
Created room: RZZZDY
Player A connected
Player B connected
Player A received: {"type":"player_joined","player_id":"player_B"}
Player B sent note: C4
Player A received: {"type":"note","instrument":"piano","note":"C4"}
Player A sent note: kick
Player B received: {"type":"note","instrument":"drums","note":"kick"}
```

All 5 checks pass:
- ✅ Both players connect successfully
- ✅ Join notification received by existing player
- ✅ Piano notes broadcast from B → A
- ✅ Drum notes broadcast from A → B
- ✅ Static pages and API endpoints remain accessible

